article.headline: Seven Kings score in double figures
article.linkText: Kings stop Sonics 3-game winning streak cold
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Peja Stojakovic usually needs only a few inches to get off his shots. The Seattle SuperSonics gave him considerably more -- with predictable results. Stojakovic hit six 3-pointers among his 24 points, and Bobby Jackson had 21 points and seven assists in the Sacramento Kings' 130-99 victory Sunday night. Sacramento had the highest-scoring performance in the NBA this season and its biggest margin of victory ever over Seattle, surpassing a 29-point win last season. The Kings had a season-high 37 assists and shot a season-best 58.4 percent. The combination of the Kings' fluid passing with the Sonics' static defense produced a laughably uneven game. Even Stojakovic and Jackson seemed a bit surprised by the sheer number of open shots they got. "When you get up that much on a lot of teams, they're most definitely going to quit," Jackson said. "That's our responsibility, though. It's our job to make sure they don't feel like they can come back." Brad Miller had 16 points and 11 rebounds for the Kings, who improved the NBA's best record to 23-8. The Sonics' three-game winning streak was snapped by the Kings' third straight victory. Doug Christie had 14 points, eight assists and five rebounds as the Kings took a 20-point lead in the first half and a 36-point lead late in the third quarter. Stojakovic, the NBA's second-leading scorer, finished one shy of his career high for 3-pointers despite sitting out the last 10 minutes as the Kings improved to 17-2 at home. Rashard Lewis scored 18 points for the Sonics, mostly lifeless two nights after beating the Los Angeles Lakers. Seattle couldn't guard the Kings' offensive machine, and guard Ray Allen managed just eight points on 4-of-12 shooting. "They basically did whatever they wanted," Seattle coach Nate McMillan said. "They just picked whoever they wanted to go after defensively, and we didn't play defense. Offensively, (we had) absolutely no movement, no movement of the ball, no movement of the men." The Kings had a wealth of open shots against the Sonics, who had won three straight road games. Seattle has lost four straight to Sacramento, which won the season series between the teams last season for the first time since 1994-95. Sacramento closed the first half with a 15-6 run keyed by eight straight points from Stojakovic, who hit four 3-pointers in the first half. Mike Bibby, who had 13 points and six assists, hit a jumper with 2.8 seconds left to give the Kings a 63-43 halftime lead. "They beat us in all facets of the game," Allen said. "Every little mistake, they exploited. Our emotions weren't high, and you have to fight through that. It seemed like everyone had heavy legs. We were stuck in first or second gear." The Kings poured it on in the third quarter, making another 15-6 run and entering the fourth up 99-65. They showed no adverse affects from a draining road win over the Clippers a night earlier, still looking fresh after a five-day break before the trip to Los Angeles. "We knew we have a tough month coming up, and we had to raise our energy level tonight," Kings coach Rick Adelman said. "They were missing a lot of their shots, and we came out with a lot of open shots, and that's when we really put them away." Sacramento moved past the Lakers for the league's best record over the weekend, and the Kings are in position to improve their standing. They began a stretch with six of nine games at home with one of their easiest victories of the season. Reggie Evans scored 16 points for Seattle, and Vladimir Radmanovic had 12 points and six rebounds.

Game notes
F Gerald Wallace missed his second game following a death in his family, leaving the Kings with just 10 players in uniform. Lawrence Funderburke is on the active roster, but he probably won't play this season with a heel injury. ... The teams meet again in Seattle on Wednesday. They'll finish their season series with two more games in four days on Jan. 31 and Feb. 3. ... Seattle has lost its last three games at Arco Arena by an average of 27.3 points per game.
